WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.240 --> 00:00:01.560
Hello.

2
00:00:02.740 --> 00:00:02.980
Good.

3
00:00:03.690 --> 00:00:03.690
Good.

4
00:00:04.580 --> 00:00:08.280
Good afternoon, everyone. Welcome to our mini symposium on

5
00:00:08.700 --> 00:00:12.660
genomic approaches to understanding tumor evolution. I'm Hui Shen.

6
00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:16.750
I'm from the Van Andel Institute in Grand Rapids, Michigan, and I'm co-chairing

7
00:00:16.800 --> 00:00:20.740
this session with Dr. Arnav Mehta, oncologist

8
00:00:20.780 --> 00:00:23.400
from Stanford and venture partner from the Column Group.

9
00:00:24.720 --> 00:00:28.530
Let me set the stage briefly. So the central

10
00:00:28.560 --> 00:00:32.420
problem for cancer evolution can be put quite simply,

11
00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:36.420
tumors change. So they change as they develop, as they spread,

12
00:00:36.860 --> 00:00:40.620
as we treat them. And these changes can be genetic

13
00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:44.540
or non-genetic, and interact with the selective

14
00:00:44.660 --> 00:00:47.660
microenvironment, and at any point can consist of functional or

15
00:00:47.780 --> 00:00:51.280
driver or non-functional or passenger events.

16
00:00:52.860 --> 00:00:56.260
So genomic profiling is a very powerful tool in

17
00:00:56.300 --> 00:00:59.760
profiling and cataloging these events, and

18
00:00:59.820 --> 00:01:00.510
increasingly,

19
00:01:01.440 --> 00:01:05.220
to decode the logic behind them. So we're at a

20
00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:08.740
moment where cataloging is turning into interpretations, and

21
00:01:08.780 --> 00:01:10.190
we try to understand

22
00:01:11.420 --> 00:01:12.160
which of these

23
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.900
changes matter, when they occur, and why they occur, where

24
00:01:16.960 --> 00:01:17.380
they do.

25
00:01:18.500 --> 00:01:22.200
So we have seven great talks today that

26
00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:24.060
showcase the power of genomic

27
00:01:25.100 --> 00:01:28.300
methods in tracking and understanding these changes

28
00:01:28.780 --> 00:01:32.480
in tumor evolution. And these talks

29
00:01:32.540 --> 00:01:36.280
covers cancers that arise from different organ sites, and they

30
00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:40.920
methodologically

31
00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:44.180
span the full modern toolkit of whole genome

32
00:01:44.820 --> 00:01:48.600
functional screens, population scale whole genome sequencing, whole exome

33
00:01:48.660 --> 00:01:52.220
sequencing, single cell multi-omics, spatial transcriptomics,

34
00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:55.500
and so will be truly

35
00:01:56.140 --> 00:01:59.740
intellectually stimulating today.

36
00:02:00.040 --> 00:02:03.410
Each talk will be 10 minutes, followed by a five-minute Q&amp;A session.

37
00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:07.680
For the audience with questions, please come to these mics so everybody can hear

38
00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:11.120
you. And then Dr. Mehta will deliver the

39
00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:15.070
closing remarks. Without much ado, let's get

40
00:02:15.120 --> 00:02:17.690
started. Please welcome our first speaker, Dr.

41
00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:20.530
Charlotte Grieco from CRUK.

42
00:02:29.620 --> 00:02:32.160
Good afternoon. My name is Charlotte Grieco.

43
00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:36.120
I am a medical oncology resident in London, and a clinical PhD

44
00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:38.700
student with Charlie Swanton at the Francis Crick Institute.

45
00:02:39.780 --> 00:02:43.090
I'm very pleased today to present our work on multiple primary lung cancers within

46
00:02:43.200 --> 00:02:43.920
TRACERx.

47
00:02:45.780 --> 00:02:47.340
And I have no financial relationships.

48
00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:52.160
So multiple primary lung cancers represent a growing clinical challenge.

49
00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:55.900
Improved lung cancer survival over the last 50 years

50
00:02:56.600 --> 00:02:59.980
has increased the window of opportunity for second primaries occurring.

51
00:03:01.040 --> 00:03:04.740
Lung cancer survivors also have a five times greater risk of a second

52
00:03:04.780 --> 00:03:07.160
primary tumor relative to the general

53
00:03:07.170 --> 00:03:11.000
population. But distinguishing second primaries

54
00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:14.880
from relapses or metastases represents a major unmet need.

55
00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:18.300
Limited clinical criteria exist.

56
00:03:18.720 --> 00:03:22.200
We use the timing of events, clinical reports, and

57
00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:26.040
pathological interpretation to try and disentangle this, but there's no

58
00:03:26.060 --> 00:03:27.340
definitive gold standard.

59
00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:31.370
Despite recommendations for the use of sequencing in this

60
00:03:31.400 --> 00:03:33.900
context, this is heavily underutilized,

61
00:03:34.940 --> 00:03:38.800
and understanding the genomic and molecular determinations

62
00:03:39.640 --> 00:03:43.290
of these tumors remains unclear. Prior studies

63
00:03:43.340 --> 00:03:44.980
include pre-invasive lesions,

64
00:03:45.980 --> 00:03:49.549
cohorts are skewed towards East Asian predominant genetic

65
00:03:49.620 --> 00:03:53.160
ancestry, and many of the studies use panel

66
00:03:53.220 --> 00:03:54.540
sequencing to do this.

67
00:03:56.620 --> 00:04:00.140
TRACERx was designed to study the evolution of non-small cell lung

68
00:04:00.220 --> 00:04:04.060
cancer from early stage through complete surgical resection,

69
00:04:04.470 --> 00:04:06.640
through recurrence or cure.

70
00:04:08.380 --> 00:04:11.960
Patients were permitted to have more than one primary tumor, as long as both

71
00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:15.560
primary tumors at the time of registration were treated with curative

72
00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:16.120
intent.

73
00:04:17.079 --> 00:04:20.601
These patients were then followed up over time, undergoing sampling of

74
00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:24.620
metastatic disease, but also sampling of new primary tumors should they

75
00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:25.820
occur during follow-up.

76
00:04:27.060 --> 00:04:30.960
All samples were subject to high-depth whole exome sequencing, as well

77
00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.060
as other molecular characterizations.

78
00:04:33.900 --> 00:04:37.580
We can use all of this data, plus detailed clinical data, to

79
00:04:37.640 --> 00:04:41.120
understand the evolution of these tumors within the patient host,

80
00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:43.820
either single tumors or multiple tumors.

81
00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:49.740
So the overarching aim of our project is to characterize multiple lung

82
00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:53.510
primaries through integrated genomic, microenvironmental,

83
00:04:53.800 --> 00:04:57.380
and clinical data to try to improve diagnosis and to

84
00:04:57.440 --> 00:04:58.800
inform treatment strategies.

85
00:04:59.840 --> 00:05:01.700
Today, I'll address three main questions.

86
00:05:02.440 --> 00:05:06.040
Firstly, how confidently can we distinguish these multiple

87
00:05:06.120 --> 00:05:07.940
primaries from metastases?

88
00:05:08.960 --> 00:05:12.540
Secondly, what's driving multiple primary tumors within patients?

89
00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.560
Is it germline risk, or are there features of environmental exposure

90
00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:17.520
affecting the host?

91
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.410
And finally, how molecularly similar are these tumors within patients?

92
00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:28.600
We define multiple primary tumors in TRACERx in several ways.

93
00:05:29.820 --> 00:05:31.469
Firstly, a patient may have had

94
00:05:32.400 --> 00:05:36.040
a prior cancer before study recruitment, but this must have

95
00:05:36.080 --> 00:05:38.850
occurred more than three years prior to registration.

96
00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:43.880
Secondly, a patient may have had synchronous primary tumors, both

97
00:05:43.900 --> 00:05:45.580
present on the baseline imaging.

98
00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:50.120
Often, these tumors are resected at separate time points.

99
00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:56.140
Finally, a patient may develop a metachronous

100
00:05:56.180 --> 00:06:00.100
tumor occurring during the follow-up time period, either within

101
00:06:00.140 --> 00:06:02.060
the lung or within another organ

102
00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:05.980
site.Using the whole exome

103
00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:10.000
sequencing data available for these patients, we were able to compare the

104
00:06:10.020 --> 00:06:13.840
genomic relatedness versus clinical determinations of

105
00:06:13.900 --> 00:06:15.480
these multiple primary tumors.

106
00:06:16.660 --> 00:06:20.360
So in the clinic, relatedness is determined through pathology review,

107
00:06:20.860 --> 00:06:24.120
review of imaging, and also assessing the timing of these events.

108
00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:29.820
We define genomic relatedness of tumors as the sharing of 10 or

109
00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:32.500
more mutations through whole exome sequencing.

110
00:06:33.780 --> 00:06:37.760
And across the cohort, we see that there is a 10% discordance

111
00:06:37.820 --> 00:06:39.720
in clinical and genomic relatedness.

112
00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:43.360
This occurs in several ways.

113
00:06:44.200 --> 00:06:47.510
Firstly, at baseline, we saw that 3 out of 30

114
00:06:47.820 --> 00:06:51.440
genomically unrelated pairs were clinically treated as metastases.

115
00:06:52.380 --> 00:06:54.880
Now, this has significant implications for treatment.

116
00:06:55.420 --> 00:06:59.400
This may have upstaged patients, and they may have therefore had adjuvant

117
00:06:59.460 --> 00:07:01.180
therapy that was perhaps not required.

118
00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:07.120
Secondly, during follow-up, this occurs in

119
00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:08.000
two directions.

120
00:07:09.900 --> 00:07:13.770
Firstly, we observed that five genomically unrelated pairs were

121
00:07:13.860 --> 00:07:15.480
actually diagnosed as metastases.

122
00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:20.470
More commonly, however, we saw that 11 genomically related

123
00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:22.780
tumors were diagnosed as new primaries.

124
00:07:24.340 --> 00:07:26.620
And this, again, has significant implications.

125
00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:30.720
These patients potentially had stage four disease and then didn't actually get the

126
00:07:30.740 --> 00:07:33.000
systemic therapy that they may have needed.

127
00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:40.240
So 1 in 10 patients were perhaps not accurately diagnosed and treated

128
00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:44.540
as a result of not using sequencing of their relapse or

129
00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:45.540
new primary lesions.

130
00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:49.290
So how does our cohort look?

131
00:07:50.800 --> 00:07:54.660
Across all patients in TRACERx, we see 25% have more than

132
00:07:54.720 --> 00:07:58.700
one primary tumor. The range is from one to four

133
00:07:58.780 --> 00:08:00.040
additional primary tumors.

134
00:08:02.080 --> 00:08:06.000
Looking across tumor subtypes, you can see that the vast majority of these tumors

135
00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:07.180
are occurring within the lung,

136
00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:11.720
with approximately half of these occurring at baseline and half during

137
00:08:11.760 --> 00:08:12.240
follow-up.

138
00:08:13.580 --> 00:08:17.149
Interestingly, those with a prior cancer, representing about

139
00:08:17.180 --> 00:08:20.100
10% of the cohort, span multiple organ

140
00:08:20.220 --> 00:08:23.940
sites. However, when we look at tumors occurring during follow-up,

141
00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:28.300
they're more likely to occur in smoking-related tumors, such as upper

142
00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:29.280
GI or bladder.

143
00:08:30.980 --> 00:08:34.300
For the rest of the talk, I'll focus on the lung multiple primary cohort.

144
00:08:36.780 --> 00:08:40.560
12% of patients in TRACERx had more than one lung multiple primary.

145
00:08:42.020 --> 00:08:45.900
The majority had just one additional tumor, either occurring at baseline

146
00:08:46.340 --> 00:08:47.260
or during follow-up.

147
00:08:48.240 --> 00:08:52.220
However, a small proportion of patients had more than one additional lung cancer,

148
00:08:52.860 --> 00:08:56.140
and these represent our greatest clinical unmet need.

149
00:08:57.720 --> 00:09:00.940
The shaded bars demonstrate those for which we have sequencing data for.

150
00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:06.060
This cohort is 114 tumors across 58

151
00:09:06.100 --> 00:09:06.640
patients.

152
00:09:09.780 --> 00:09:13.000
So now looking at the histological

153
00:09:13.340 --> 00:09:16.140
landscape of our cohort, which you can see here.

154
00:09:17.180 --> 00:09:20.220
Each column represents a patient and each row a tumor.

155
00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:25.400
Adenocarcinomas are seen in the dark red, squamous carcinomas

156
00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:29.460
in dark blue, and other non-small cell lung cancers are seen

157
00:09:29.500 --> 00:09:30.240
in gray.

158
00:09:31.460 --> 00:09:34.100
Clearly, adenocarcinomas dominate this landscape.

159
00:09:35.340 --> 00:09:39.220
Of note, if you look at the lower bar here of smoking status, you can see that

160
00:09:39.260 --> 00:09:43.100
most patients have some sort of smoking exposure, with only three patients

161
00:09:43.340 --> 00:09:44.360
being never smokers.

162
00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:45.580
This is a

163
00:09:47.300 --> 00:09:51.180
much lower proportion than you might expect to see in a UK lung cancer cohort.

164
00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:57.200
We look to explore the pairwise differences in histology across the cohort

165
00:09:57.280 --> 00:10:00.740
by comparing the baseline tumor histology to the additional tumors.

166
00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:05.240
And here you can see that there is a patient-specific tendency towards

167
00:10:05.280 --> 00:10:08.400
histology, particularly seen within the LUAD subtype.

168
00:10:09.320 --> 00:10:12.520
Now, this may be due to host factors or environmental

169
00:10:12.580 --> 00:10:13.320
exposures.

170
00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:18.820
We started to then look at what might be driving these multiple lung primary

171
00:10:18.880 --> 00:10:19.320
tumors.

172
00:10:20.500 --> 00:10:24.480
Firstly, we looked at germline pathogenic variants in cancer predisposition

173
00:10:24.560 --> 00:10:28.400
genes, and we didn't see an enrichment in the cohort with multiple lung

174
00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:29.260
primary tumors.

175
00:10:30.680 --> 00:10:34.540
However, when we reviewed cumulative tobacco exposure measured

176
00:10:34.580 --> 00:10:37.820
through pack-year history, we saw a significantly higher

177
00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:42.180
median pack-year history in the

178
00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:43.700
lung multiple primary cohort.

179
00:10:45.460 --> 00:10:45.640
This

180
00:10:47.220 --> 00:10:51.180
suggests that perhaps germline predisposition is not as important as

181
00:10:51.220 --> 00:10:54.360
environmental exposures in developing more than one lung cancer.

182
00:10:56.820 --> 00:11:00.520
We then sought to explore the genomic characteristics of tumors from patients with

183
00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:03.620
multiple primaries versus those with only one lung cancer.

184
00:11:04.640 --> 00:11:06.400
We explored three genomic metrics:

185
00:11:07.220 --> 00:11:10.810
chromosomal instability measured through the weighted genome instability

186
00:11:10.860 --> 00:11:14.800
index, mutations per tumor, and also the rate of driver

187
00:11:14.840 --> 00:11:18.360
mutations. As you can see, there is no significant

188
00:11:18.420 --> 00:11:22.120
difference between tumors from patients with a single primary versus

189
00:11:22.180 --> 00:11:23.800
those with multiple primary tumors.

190
00:11:25.560 --> 00:11:29.040
So multiple primary tumors do not seem to have distinct genomic

191
00:11:29.100 --> 00:11:29.640
features.

192
00:11:33.140 --> 00:11:36.659
Finally, we sought to understand whether tumors within a

193
00:11:36.700 --> 00:11:39.130
patient shared common driver pathways.

194
00:11:40.380 --> 00:11:42.040
We looked at the proportion of

195
00:11:43.380 --> 00:11:47.000
mutations in shared driver genes within patients,

196
00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:50.020
seen here at 12% in the red dashed line.

197
00:11:50.980 --> 00:11:54.460
We performed permutation testing where we took random pairs of

198
00:11:54.480 --> 00:11:57.760
tumors from the cohort matched by histology and smoking

199
00:11:57.800 --> 00:12:01.400
status to see whether there was any specific enrichment in

200
00:12:01.440 --> 00:12:05.100
mutations in shared genes within patients.

201
00:12:05.120 --> 00:12:07.930
And as you can see here, there's no specific enrichment within

202
00:12:07.980 --> 00:12:11.974
patients.So we can

203
00:12:12.004 --> 00:12:15.924
conclude that multiple primary tumors seem to be as genomically divergent

204
00:12:15.964 --> 00:12:18.844
as those from different patients altogether.

205
00:12:18.884 --> 00:12:22.784
This supports the hypothesis that independent tumor initiation events are

206
00:12:22.824 --> 00:12:25.924
likely driven in this cohort by stochastic

207
00:12:26.224 --> 00:12:29.164
exposure-related mutagenesis rather than a

208
00:12:29.204 --> 00:12:31.564
patient-specific pathway.

209
00:12:33.524 --> 00:12:37.404
I think this is particularly interesting because these tumors look

210
00:12:37.444 --> 00:12:41.424
as different as any tumors from

211
00:12:41.464 --> 00:12:45.344
any patient, but they've developed within the same host with the

212
00:12:45.384 --> 00:12:46.904
same environmental exposures.

213
00:12:49.664 --> 00:12:52.664
So to conclude, multiple primary tumors are common.

214
00:12:53.404 --> 00:12:56.764
25% of TRACERx patients have more than one primary cancer,

215
00:12:57.444 --> 00:12:59.414
and 12% more than one lung primary.

216
00:13:00.764 --> 00:13:04.284
One in 10 cases were clinically misclassified without using

217
00:13:04.304 --> 00:13:07.914
whole-exome sequencing data, risking inappropriate treatment for those

218
00:13:07.984 --> 00:13:08.524
cases.

219
00:13:09.844 --> 00:13:13.824
Tumors within a patient are likely to share histology, but genomically

220
00:13:13.884 --> 00:13:16.784
they seem as divergent as tumors between patients.

221
00:13:17.904 --> 00:13:21.624
Our future work will combine these genomic insights with host

222
00:13:21.724 --> 00:13:25.634
immune factors and also therapy data to try and

223
00:13:25.664 --> 00:13:29.104
understand why these tumors are evolving independently within

224
00:13:29.164 --> 00:13:30.884
patients and how that might be occurring.

225
00:13:32.344 --> 00:13:35.964
I'd like to extend a special thanks to the team, particularly Lydia,

226
00:13:36.164 --> 00:13:39.854
Adriana, and Christina, who've put a lot of time and effort into this project, as

227
00:13:39.884 --> 00:13:43.524
well as the other clinicians, pathologists, and bioinformaticians you can see here.

228
00:13:45.104 --> 00:13:48.894
I'd also like to acknowledge the wider lab team, all our funders,

229
00:13:49.004 --> 00:13:52.824
including Cancer Research UK, and of course, the patients and their families

230
00:13:52.844 --> 00:13:53.944
involved in TRACERx.

231
00:14:01.364 --> 00:14:04.604
Thank you very much, Charlotte. Do we have questions from the audience?

232
00:14:05.724 --> 00:14:07.124
Please come to the mic, please. Thank you.

233
00:14:07.764 --> 00:14:10.704
Thank you very much for the nice presentation. I have a question.

234
00:14:10.784 --> 00:14:14.264
Why do you define relatedness based only on SNVs,

235
00:14:14.684 --> 00:14:16.964
and why not copy number alterations?

236
00:14:17.004 --> 00:14:20.943
In other words, I think it's really unlikely for two unrelated

237
00:14:20.984 --> 00:14:23.424
tumors to share a common breakpoint.

238
00:14:24.224 --> 00:14:28.124
It's a very good question. Today, in 10 minutes, I'm only able to show a small

239
00:14:28.184 --> 00:14:30.904
amount of data, but this is something we are also looking at.

240
00:14:33.364 --> 00:14:35.724
That was actually my question, but now I have another one.

241
00:14:36.484 --> 00:14:40.064
When you said you define clonal relatedness greater than 10 mutations-

242
00:14:40.224 --> 00:14:40.233
Yes

243
00:14:40.233 --> 00:14:42.884
... is that correct? And these are any, not drivers.

244
00:14:43.244 --> 00:14:43.504
Yes.

245
00:14:45.324 --> 00:14:49.064
So I can explain the process. So we basically generate these

246
00:14:49.104 --> 00:14:51.664
sequencing heat maps, and we compare

247
00:14:52.524 --> 00:14:56.464
within patients the tumors, but we look at the distribution of the

248
00:14:56.504 --> 00:14:59.144
mutations across the variants called.

249
00:14:59.224 --> 00:15:02.264
So we can see very clear, separate clonal populations in making those

250
00:15:02.304 --> 00:15:03.344
definitions.

251
00:15:03.404 --> 00:15:06.924
I might have missed this, but did you show that in the multiple lung primaries,

252
00:15:07.144 --> 00:15:08.584
what was the shared drivers?

253
00:15:09.724 --> 00:15:10.964
As in specific genes?

254
00:15:11.284 --> 00:15:14.714
Specific lung, like EGFR mutations,

255
00:15:14.884 --> 00:15:16.474
ROS1, ALK fusions.

256
00:15:16.764 --> 00:15:20.324
We don't see much evidence of shared drivers actually at all.

257
00:15:20.364 --> 00:15:24.004
And within this cohort, there's only one patient with an EGFR mutation that's a

258
00:15:24.024 --> 00:15:24.864
driver mutation.

259
00:15:25.264 --> 00:15:25.274
Wow.

260
00:15:25.284 --> 00:15:26.724
So it's not

261
00:15:27.704 --> 00:15:31.064
obvious clinical drivers that we might target in the clinic that we see in this

262
00:15:31.104 --> 00:15:32.144
population generally.

263
00:15:32.984 --> 00:15:35.554
There are some drivers shared, often TP53,

264
00:15:36.624 --> 00:15:38.784
but they don't seem to be enriched really.

265
00:15:39.164 --> 00:15:39.764
Okay, thank you.

266
00:15:42.804 --> 00:15:44.964
Are there any more questions from the audience?

267
00:15:45.824 --> 00:15:49.744
If not, I have one that's related to both the two questions

268
00:15:49.864 --> 00:15:52.733
asked. So you used 10 as the cutoff for the mutation-

269
00:15:52.904 --> 00:15:52.914
Mm-hmm

270
00:15:52.924 --> 00:15:55.044
... to call whether it's genomically related or not.

271
00:15:55.124 --> 00:15:55.414
Mm-hmm.

272
00:15:55.904 --> 00:15:59.564
So what is the overall distribution of the shared number of

273
00:15:59.624 --> 00:16:01.744
mutation look like? So why specifically 10?

274
00:16:01.864 --> 00:16:02.004
And

275
00:16:03.084 --> 00:16:07.004
are there any mutation-sparse tumors

276
00:16:07.124 --> 00:16:09.704
that this absolute number would be

277
00:16:10.584 --> 00:16:13.244
difficult to use? Yeah.

278
00:16:13.584 --> 00:16:16.444
So the cutoff of 10 was established a long time before I joined the lab.

279
00:16:16.644 --> 00:16:16.844
Uh-huh.

280
00:16:17.324 --> 00:16:21.284
And actually, I think from the evidence we've shown, the fact that it's very

281
00:16:21.304 --> 00:16:25.124
unlikely even to share any driver mutations, I think 10 is actually quite a

282
00:16:25.144 --> 00:16:26.044
rigorous cutoff.

283
00:16:26.224 --> 00:16:26.424
Mm-hmm.

284
00:16:27.303 --> 00:16:27.483
Yeah.

285
00:16:28.604 --> 00:16:28.983
Thank you.

286
00:16:30.144 --> 00:16:31.344
I have one other question.

287
00:16:32.604 --> 00:16:36.224
Do you see any survival differences for patients that have

288
00:16:36.264 --> 00:16:39.904
multiple primaries? Do you think of them as sort of independent events that

289
00:16:40.304 --> 00:16:42.384
kind of influence survival, or is there some-

290
00:16:43.344 --> 00:16:43.664
Mm-hmm

291
00:16:44.004 --> 00:16:44.584
... relationship?

292
00:16:45.164 --> 00:16:48.994
So I haven't shown this data today, but we do see some survival differences

293
00:16:49.004 --> 00:16:52.784
within the cohort. We have to kind of split this up based on the type of

294
00:16:52.824 --> 00:16:55.824
multiple primary that the patient had because, of course, the treatment differs in

295
00:16:55.864 --> 00:16:56.324
each group.

296
00:16:57.664 --> 00:17:01.284
For those with synchronous primaries, we do see that their survival is

297
00:17:01.324 --> 00:17:04.785
poorer, but I think it's quite hard to disentangle whether this is due to the

298
00:17:05.024 --> 00:17:08.104
cancer progression or whether it's a factor of treatment-related

299
00:17:08.984 --> 00:17:10.003
toxicity or

300
00:17:12.464 --> 00:17:13.684
treatment-related side effects.

301
00:17:14.524 --> 00:17:18.325
Interestingly, in those that develop a metachronous lung cancer,

302
00:17:19.484 --> 00:17:22.724
the survival differences aren't as marked, and I wonder whether this is because

303
00:17:22.764 --> 00:17:26.545
those are patients who are already under a lung cancer pathway, they have

304
00:17:26.604 --> 00:17:28.724
close follow-up, and we're picking them up quite early.

305
00:17:30.084 --> 00:17:32.563
Fantastic. Thank you, Charlotte.

306
00:17:34.104 --> 00:17:34.974
Okay.

307
00:17:35.964 --> 00:17:36.784
Thank you.

308
00:17:36.834 --> 00:17:40.284
Great. Next, we have Sebastian Mueller from the Technical University of

309
00:17:40.544 --> 00:17:43.584
Munich, who's going to tell us about the Mouse Cancer Cell Line Atlas.

310
00:17:45.664 --> 00:17:46.304
Thank you very much.

311
00:17:48.284 --> 00:17:51.924
So yeah, thank you very much for giving me the opportunity to speak here

312
00:17:51.984 --> 00:17:53.724
today and to present our work.

313
00:17:54.964 --> 00:17:56.084
I have nothing to disclose.

314
00:17:58.124 --> 00:18:01.584
To start with, the Human Cancer Cell Line Encyclopedia has become an

315
00:18:01.644 --> 00:18:05.604
indispensable resource in cancer research, not only because of

316
00:18:05.684 --> 00:18:09.384
the systematic characterization of these cell lines at different

317
00:18:09.464 --> 00:18:13.364
levels, but also through the chance of functional perturbating

318
00:18:13.384 --> 00:18:14.604
those cell lines.

319
00:18:15.760 --> 00:18:19.680
However, no such resource exists for the mouse, despite

320
00:18:19.720 --> 00:18:23.540
the fact that the mouse is the most important mammalian model

321
00:18:23.640 --> 00:18:25.220
organism in cancer research.

322
00:18:26.800 --> 00:18:30.280
So because of that, we initiated the Mouse Cancer Cell Line Atlas,

323
00:18:30.880 --> 00:18:34.740
which so far comprises 590 different cell

324
00:18:34.780 --> 00:18:38.540
lines from 22 different lineages, as you can see here.

325
00:18:39.250 --> 00:18:42.820
And we systematically characterize these cell lines at multiple levels, so

326
00:18:42.900 --> 00:18:46.560
genomics, transcriptomics, cell morphology, histopathology,

327
00:18:46.690 --> 00:18:50.120
clinical metadata, and we also annotated

328
00:18:50.160 --> 00:18:51.010
immunophenotypes.

329
00:18:51.880 --> 00:18:55.340
So what are these immunophenotypes or what is the

330
00:18:55.360 --> 00:18:56.860
immunophenotype of a mouse cell line?

331
00:18:57.500 --> 00:19:01.340
We define it from three factors: genetic background, MHC

332
00:19:01.400 --> 00:19:02.460
haplotype, and gender.

333
00:19:03.600 --> 00:19:07.400
And why is that important? Because in contrast to human cell

334
00:19:07.410 --> 00:19:11.400
lines, we can transplant mouse cell lines into immunocompetent mice.

335
00:19:12.900 --> 00:19:14.640
But the only problem here is that

336
00:19:15.580 --> 00:19:18.540
typically, the immunophenotype of a mouse line is not well known.

337
00:19:19.280 --> 00:19:23.180
So because of that problem, we developed a computational

338
00:19:23.260 --> 00:19:26.440
tool, StrainMapper, which allows us to

339
00:19:26.960 --> 00:19:30.420
identify genetic background, MHC haplotype, and gender

340
00:19:30.480 --> 00:19:33.580
from genomic sequencing data of a mouse

341
00:19:33.620 --> 00:19:35.590
line. Once we know that,

342
00:19:36.420 --> 00:19:38.620
so we did that for all 590

343
00:19:39.640 --> 00:19:43.220
MCCA lines, and once we have this immunophenotype

344
00:19:43.260 --> 00:19:46.680
information, we can precisely match the mouse line to an

345
00:19:46.720 --> 00:19:50.560
immunocompetent recipient mouse, which then allows us to use these

346
00:19:50.620 --> 00:19:52.600
lines for immunocompetent transplantations.

347
00:19:54.340 --> 00:19:57.920
So all the data that we generated in the Mouse Cancer Cell Line

348
00:19:57.960 --> 00:20:01.820
Atlas is available through this website, and it allows

349
00:20:01.900 --> 00:20:05.480
also to explore this data through cBioPortal Web

350
00:20:05.560 --> 00:20:06.060
Interface.

351
00:20:08.900 --> 00:20:09.100
So

352
00:20:10.220 --> 00:20:14.040
what we wanted to do with the Mouse Cancer Cell Line Atlas is to better understand

353
00:20:14.120 --> 00:20:17.880
tissue-specific cancer evolution, and this builds

354
00:20:17.920 --> 00:20:21.780
on previous work that we have done in the pancreas. So a little detour here.

355
00:20:23.240 --> 00:20:27.229
At that time, we studied KRAS driven oncogenesis in mice,

356
00:20:27.300 --> 00:20:30.360
where pancreatic cancers are induced by one copy of mutant KRAS.

357
00:20:31.180 --> 00:20:33.440
We found that two-thirds of these cancers actually

358
00:20:33.460 --> 00:20:37.440
acquired during their evolution, a second copy

359
00:20:37.480 --> 00:20:40.700
of the mutant KRAS. So this is not a high-level amplification.

360
00:20:41.100 --> 00:20:43.840
This is just one copy of mutant KRAS that is more.

361
00:20:44.620 --> 00:20:48.220
And we found that this dosage increase of the mutant allele is

362
00:20:48.240 --> 00:20:52.120
acquired relatively early during cancer evolution in the precursor

363
00:20:52.200 --> 00:20:54.500
stage, and this is also linked to metastasis.

364
00:20:55.360 --> 00:20:59.100
When the cancers do not amplify KRAS or gain a second

365
00:20:59.140 --> 00:21:02.020
copy of KRAS, they amplify alternative oncogenes.

366
00:21:03.600 --> 00:21:07.320
So to keep it short, we simplified this in a model where

367
00:21:07.340 --> 00:21:11.270
pancreatic cancer evolution starts with one copy of mutant KRAS, and

368
00:21:11.300 --> 00:21:14.940
depending on whether you gain a second copy of mutant KRAS or amplify

369
00:21:14.980 --> 00:21:18.940
alternative oncogenes, this then has important implications

370
00:21:18.980 --> 00:21:21.860
for the cancer phenotype. So metastasis,

371
00:21:22.760 --> 00:21:25.740
cell morphology, histopathology, and growth

372
00:21:25.840 --> 00:21:29.780
aggressiveness. Which way you go depends

373
00:21:29.880 --> 00:21:32.960
on the type of tumor suppressor gene loss, and this is what we found through

374
00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:36.790
phylogenetic analysis. So homozygous loss of CDKN2A

375
00:21:36.940 --> 00:21:40.380
is required to allow for this dosage gain of mutant KRAS.

376
00:21:40.900 --> 00:21:43.020
The same can be achieved through loss of p53.

377
00:21:43.600 --> 00:21:45.380
But when we knocked out TGF-beta

378
00:21:46.620 --> 00:21:47.090
pathway,

379
00:21:48.440 --> 00:21:52.240
we found that this leads only to a heterozygous loss of CDKN2A, which

380
00:21:52.300 --> 00:21:56.080
is compatible with amplification of these alternative

381
00:21:56.740 --> 00:21:57.240
oncogenes.

382
00:21:58.080 --> 00:21:59.640
So conceptually, at the time,

383
00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:04.980
we concluded that when we want to understand cancer phenotypes, in

384
00:22:05.020 --> 00:22:06.040
this case in the pancreas,

385
00:22:06.860 --> 00:22:10.500
we should not only have a look at mutations, but we need to include two additional

386
00:22:10.540 --> 00:22:14.100
dimensions, the dosage of a mutation and its evolution.

387
00:22:15.120 --> 00:22:18.580
So now we wanted to investigate if these

388
00:22:19.960 --> 00:22:23.880
insights also apply to other cancer types which have frequent KRAS mutations,

389
00:22:24.300 --> 00:22:27.580
and this is where we used the Mouse Cancer Cell Line Atlas.

390
00:22:28.060 --> 00:22:31.920
So we included now lung and intestinal cancers, which are

391
00:22:31.980 --> 00:22:34.340
all induced by oncogenic KRAS in the mice.

392
00:22:35.040 --> 00:22:35.870
And we found that

393
00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:40.200
all of them frequently gain a second copy of the mutant KRAS.

394
00:22:40.460 --> 00:22:44.150
So please ignore the details here. So they frequently amplify KRAS.

395
00:22:44.700 --> 00:22:48.680
The same can be seen in human cancer cell lines and human cancer tissues.

396
00:22:48.780 --> 00:22:52.500
And we also found that this dosage increase of the mutant allele has

397
00:22:52.540 --> 00:22:53.580
prognostic relevance.

398
00:22:54.480 --> 00:22:57.100
The question was then, when during cancer evolution

399
00:22:58.780 --> 00:23:02.760
dosage of KRAS is increased? And what I have just shown you before is in

400
00:23:02.800 --> 00:23:04.320
the pancreas, this is an early event.

401
00:23:05.100 --> 00:23:07.530
So when we looked at cancer evolution in

402
00:23:08.420 --> 00:23:11.820
the intestine-- So in the lung here, sorry, and in the intestine, we

403
00:23:11.860 --> 00:23:14.900
found that their dosage increase of KRAS

404
00:23:15.740 --> 00:23:17.700
typically occurs in the carcinoma state.

405
00:23:18.250 --> 00:23:21.880
So in the lung and in the intestine, KRAS

406
00:23:21.920 --> 00:23:24.780
dosage increase occurs late during cancer evolution.

407
00:23:25.240 --> 00:23:27.700
But in the pancreas, it's an early event.

408
00:23:28.310 --> 00:23:31.520
And then we, of course, wanted to know how does it come, the difference in the

409
00:23:31.580 --> 00:23:32.960
timing, and

410
00:23:34.220 --> 00:23:37.560
we performed many different experiments, and this is the one

411
00:23:38.560 --> 00:23:42.300
that was most informative for us. So here we overexpressed different

412
00:23:42.440 --> 00:23:46.020
levels of oncogenic KRAS in non-transformed

413
00:23:46.240 --> 00:23:48.260
human pancreatic and intestinal cells.

414
00:23:49.680 --> 00:23:53.610
What we found is that in both models, KRAS induces more oncogenic signaling.

415
00:23:53.920 --> 00:23:57.390
That's to be expected. But specifically in the pancreas, we found

416
00:23:57.420 --> 00:23:58.660
dedifferentiation signatures.

417
00:24:00.980 --> 00:24:04.780
We further validated this in a second model of pancreatic

418
00:24:04.840 --> 00:24:08.660
acinar cells. So here we performed a similar experiment,

419
00:24:08.820 --> 00:24:12.640
and we found that the KRAS induces dedifferentiation of acinar

420
00:24:12.680 --> 00:24:14.520
cells into ductal-like progenitor cells.

421
00:24:15.650 --> 00:24:17.320
And the interesting observation was here

422
00:24:17.420 --> 00:24:21.388
thatHigh levels of oncogenic K-RAS

423
00:24:21.488 --> 00:24:24.608
were required to induce this dedifferentiation process.

424
00:24:24.928 --> 00:24:26.748
And this case gave us the idea that

425
00:24:28.748 --> 00:24:32.228
because dedifferentiation is the very first step of oncogenesis in the pancreas,

426
00:24:33.168 --> 00:24:37.128
which requires high levels of RAS, that this is the reason why RAS is amplified so

427
00:24:37.168 --> 00:24:39.708
early during cancer evolution, specifically in the pancreas.

428
00:24:41.048 --> 00:24:43.968
In the intestine, the situation is very different.

429
00:24:44.048 --> 00:24:44.288
So

430
00:24:45.268 --> 00:24:48.668
K-RAS induced proliferation in this context, and

431
00:24:49.608 --> 00:24:52.928
this is however, not of selective advantage in the intestine

432
00:24:52.988 --> 00:24:55.848
because the intestine is anyway highly proliferative.

433
00:24:56.528 --> 00:25:00.068
So what you need to achieve is to escape this rapid epithelial

434
00:25:00.148 --> 00:25:04.008
turnover in the intestine. And this is mediated through block of

435
00:25:04.068 --> 00:25:07.168
differentiation, which is typically acquired through Wnt pathway activation.

436
00:25:08.008 --> 00:25:11.828
So if our idea is right that RAS is not

437
00:25:11.888 --> 00:25:15.708
contributing to this block of differentiation, we would expect to see Wnt pathway

438
00:25:15.768 --> 00:25:19.708
alterations in the intestine. And this is exactly what we can find here.

439
00:25:20.328 --> 00:25:20.548
So,

440
00:25:22.748 --> 00:25:23.548
in the adenomas,

441
00:25:24.788 --> 00:25:28.288
they typically acquire somatic mutations in APC and

442
00:25:28.348 --> 00:25:30.708
beta-catenin to activate the Wnt pathway.

443
00:25:31.468 --> 00:25:35.348
So remember, this is the RAS-induced, serrated

444
00:25:35.428 --> 00:25:37.228
pathway of intestinal cancer evolution.

445
00:25:37.408 --> 00:25:38.348
So which starts with

446
00:25:39.228 --> 00:25:41.908
activation of RAS, which induced proliferation,

447
00:25:42.708 --> 00:25:45.968
then we have adenoma formation, which is independent of RAS.

448
00:25:46.488 --> 00:25:50.348
Here we have the Wnt pathway activation to block differentiation, and only

449
00:25:50.428 --> 00:25:54.188
after this step is acquired, RAS can be amplified to

450
00:25:54.228 --> 00:25:56.248
drive further progression to the carcinoma state.

451
00:25:59.068 --> 00:25:59.228
So,

452
00:26:00.248 --> 00:26:00.828
what about

453
00:26:01.808 --> 00:26:03.928
K-RAS tumor suppressing interactions?

454
00:26:05.828 --> 00:26:09.328
We previously also found that CDKN2A loss is almost

455
00:26:09.428 --> 00:26:13.408
universal event in the pancreas. This is also what we see here in MCCA, but

456
00:26:13.488 --> 00:26:17.228
interestingly, this was not the case in intestinal and lung

457
00:26:17.288 --> 00:26:17.748
cancers.

458
00:26:19.268 --> 00:26:23.248
And this was a bit surprising to us, to be honest, because all these cancers are

459
00:26:23.268 --> 00:26:24.488
induced by the same oncogene.

460
00:26:25.328 --> 00:26:28.668
We found that this pattern is also conserved in human cancers.

461
00:26:29.868 --> 00:26:32.608
And then again, the question was: How does that come?

462
00:26:33.008 --> 00:26:36.997
What's the reason for that? And the explanation is relatively

463
00:26:37.108 --> 00:26:37.428
simple,

464
00:26:38.248 --> 00:26:41.568
because what we found is that the chromatin state of CDKN2A, so

465
00:26:41.668 --> 00:26:45.188
CDKN2A activity differs between healthy tissues.

466
00:26:46.008 --> 00:26:49.828
So in the pancreas, CDKN2A locus has an active

467
00:26:49.868 --> 00:26:51.488
chromatin state, so active

468
00:26:53.188 --> 00:26:56.748
histone marks, but in the intestine it's polycomb

469
00:26:56.788 --> 00:27:00.608
repressed. So the idea here is that specifically in the pancreas,

470
00:27:00.768 --> 00:27:01.368
RAS can

471
00:27:02.288 --> 00:27:06.268
activate CDKN2A mediated tumor suppression. This is why it needs to be deleted.

472
00:27:06.908 --> 00:27:09.748
And to test this, we looked at CDKN2A,

473
00:27:10.648 --> 00:27:13.228
mediated or induced senescence,

474
00:27:14.468 --> 00:27:18.448
and we found that senescence is only robustly induced by K-RAS

475
00:27:18.508 --> 00:27:22.408
in the pancreas, but not in the other tissues, explaining why it's just

476
00:27:22.488 --> 00:27:23.868
lost in the pancreas.

477
00:27:25.228 --> 00:27:27.808
Okay, so to sum that up,

478
00:27:28.708 --> 00:27:30.968
another simplified model. Here,

479
00:27:33.028 --> 00:27:35.508
cancer evolution is initiated by the same oncogene,

480
00:27:36.328 --> 00:27:36.528
and

481
00:27:37.448 --> 00:27:40.708
in all cancer types, dosage increase is a common phenomenon.

482
00:27:41.488 --> 00:27:44.608
But the timing of this dosage increase differs between the tissues.

483
00:27:44.908 --> 00:27:48.808
So in the pancreas, it's an early event because RAS

484
00:27:49.008 --> 00:27:51.568
dosage increase is required for this early dedifferentiation.

485
00:27:52.468 --> 00:27:56.268
In the intestine, it's a relatively late event because here RAS

486
00:27:56.288 --> 00:28:00.168
induces proliferation, but we need to activate Wnt pathway

487
00:28:00.248 --> 00:28:03.428
to escape this rapid epithelial turnover.

488
00:28:05.268 --> 00:28:09.128
And after block of differentiation is acquired, RAS dosage increase can

489
00:28:09.168 --> 00:28:10.088
drive progression to

490
00:28:11.068 --> 00:28:11.808
the carcinoma.

491
00:28:14.148 --> 00:28:17.938
What's also interesting about this

492
00:28:18.008 --> 00:28:21.388
model is it can explain an old observation in

493
00:28:22.468 --> 00:28:26.188
mice where K-RAS is induced in all cells of the body.

494
00:28:27.068 --> 00:28:30.808
These mice typically develop lung cancer, but not intestinal or

495
00:28:30.848 --> 00:28:33.378
pancreatic cancers. And the answer to that is,

496
00:28:34.228 --> 00:28:38.137
because in the pancreas, tumorigenesis is restrained by

497
00:28:38.148 --> 00:28:42.028
CDKN2A. In the intestine, it requires Wnt pathway

498
00:28:42.068 --> 00:28:45.208
activation. But in the lung, no such barrier exists.

499
00:28:45.628 --> 00:28:48.868
And because of that, RAS can drive

500
00:28:49.268 --> 00:28:51.798
multifocal lung carcinogenesis in this

501
00:28:51.848 --> 00:28:54.208
tissue. Okay.

502
00:28:55.028 --> 00:28:58.697
With that, I would like to finish and thank all our collaborators for their

503
00:28:58.728 --> 00:29:00.328
generous support.

504
00:29:02.828 --> 00:29:06.268
Big thanks also to Roland and Dieter supporting all of this, and

505
00:29:06.648 --> 00:29:09.968
Niklas and Marcus, who did a great job on this

506
00:29:10.188 --> 00:29:12.568
project and was happy to work with them together.

507
00:29:12.688 --> 00:29:14.428
So yeah, thanks for your attention.

508
00:29:19.988 --> 00:29:22.068
We welcome any questions at the microphone.

