754
00:43:43.962 --> 00:43:47.642
with each subtype in the column. It can sometimes be daunting to look at

755
00:43:47.702 --> 00:43:49.562
smoking signatures in lung cancer.

756
00:43:49.982 --> 00:43:52.802
I think people presume that your

757
00:43:54.642 --> 00:43:55.522
lung cancer genome

758
00:43:56.862 --> 00:44:00.742
almost won't be worth assessing. So it was really nice to see that we start

759
00:44:00.782 --> 00:44:04.262
to see some order when we look through the lens of KRAS mutant

760
00:44:04.322 --> 00:44:06.802
subtypes in terms of smoking contributions.

761
00:44:07.682 --> 00:44:11.382
And for instance, it does seem like smoking may select for

762
00:44:11.702 --> 00:44:15.602
variants like 13D and 12A, but it doesn't have a dominant

763
00:44:15.662 --> 00:44:17.782
contribution, but it's always present.

764
00:44:18.182 --> 00:44:21.902
With 12D, perhaps not. There's tumors that don't

765
00:44:21.962 --> 00:44:25.322
have any smoking contribution, and it's light when

766
00:44:25.382 --> 00:44:28.942
it's present. And 12V is interesting because there's

767
00:44:29.042 --> 00:44:32.862
dominant smoking contribution, but some tumors in there that don't

768
00:44:32.922 --> 00:44:34.902
have any smoking contribution at all.

769
00:44:35.502 --> 00:44:39.262
I think it's reasonable that we can now say that 12C and 13C are

770
00:44:39.342 --> 00:44:42.022
smoking related based on this analysis.

771
00:44:42.702 --> 00:44:46.622
And I'll finish off by just reminding you this is as robust

772
00:44:46.632 --> 00:44:49.201
an analysis that we could think of for this question.

773
00:44:49.882 --> 00:44:53.752
We used a very large whole genome sequencing cohort, and we could look at

774
00:44:53.762 --> 00:44:57.051
rare variants as well. We've done an unsupervised and supervised

775
00:44:57.082 --> 00:45:00.042
analysis. I haven't been able to show you, we've been

776
00:45:00.862 --> 00:45:04.302
able to do some co-mutational profiling and also some

777
00:45:04.362 --> 00:45:08.282
epidemiological overlay with smoking information as well to validate

778
00:45:08.342 --> 00:45:12.222
this. The take homes are indirectly, without doubt,

779
00:45:12.402 --> 00:45:16.232
KRAS mutant lung cancer associates with smoking, and to a lesser

780
00:45:16.282 --> 00:45:19.162
extent, chromosomal stability. But the direct

781
00:45:19.182 --> 00:45:22.362
impact of smoking seems to be there only for

782
00:45:22.742 --> 00:45:24.762
12C, 13C, and 12V.

783
00:45:26.202 --> 00:45:30.012
And lastly, I've mentioned the potential impact this could

784
00:45:30.102 --> 00:45:33.022
have in the clinic in the day-to-day in terms of smoking stigma.

785
00:45:33.602 --> 00:45:37.502
But reasonably, I think this work could be extended and

786
00:45:37.562 --> 00:45:41.342
used to inform public health messaging and personalized prevention in the

787
00:45:41.382 --> 00:45:45.192
future. So I'll thank David Wedge and his

788
00:45:45.242 --> 00:45:48.142
lab, who really had the intellectual input here.

789
00:45:48.362 --> 00:45:52.322
Laura's been an outstanding medical oncology fellow now

790
00:45:52.382 --> 00:45:56.282
going back to the clinic. We couldn't do anything without

791
00:45:56.922 --> 00:46:00.442
pathology and biobank services. Thanks to our funders and the

792
00:46:00.542 --> 00:46:03.902
patients and the relatives that we'll continue to advocate on their behalf.

793
00:46:12.282 --> 00:46:16.242
Fantastic talk, Colin. So maybe one question on my end is,

794
00:46:16.482 --> 00:46:20.382
we know all the RAS mutations have different hydrolysis rates and effects on MAP

795
00:46:20.402 --> 00:46:24.382
kinase signaling. And so one explanation might suggest, is there

796
00:46:24.402 --> 00:46:28.022
any reason to believe that the G12D mutations have a higher rate of

797
00:46:28.062 --> 00:46:31.602
penetrance? So even though they might be less frequent in

798
00:46:31.662 --> 00:46:35.122
pre-neoplastic lesions, that they would actually

799
00:46:35.742 --> 00:46:39.562
manifest in mature tumors. Do you have any data sets

800
00:46:39.662 --> 00:46:41.122
to compare pre-neoplastic

801
00:46:42.082 --> 00:46:43.722
distributions of RAS?

802
00:46:44.202 --> 00:46:48.182
Yeah. Great question. And I have actually heard G12D

803
00:46:48.192 --> 00:46:51.722
almost referred to as the default KRAS mutation.

804
00:46:52.582 --> 00:46:55.942
Clearly, it's the most common KRAS mutant variant as well.

805
00:46:57.922 --> 00:47:01.602
We've seen with pancreas, for instance, the variant prevalence

806
00:47:01.722 --> 00:47:05.662
seems to be matching what you see in cancer in

807
00:47:05.702 --> 00:47:08.462
the pre-neoplastic setting or the pan-in setting.

808
00:47:10.422 --> 00:47:14.312
My understanding, although TRACERx has unquestionably begun to interrogate this and

809
00:47:14.382 --> 00:47:17.742
report this, is that we don't necessarily have that level of

810
00:47:17.782 --> 00:47:21.502
information to know how much the pre-malignant tissue

811
00:47:21.562 --> 00:47:22.602
matches the cancer.

812
00:47:29.362 --> 00:47:29.782
Great.

813
00:47:30.762 --> 00:47:32.732
Any other? Great. Thank you, Colin.

814
00:47:32.742 --> 00:47:33.162
Thank you.

815
00:47:33.202 --> 00:47:33.422
Yeah.

816
00:47:38.742 --> 00:47:42.672
Right. Next we have Dr. Elizabeth Brunk from UNC Chapel Hill,

817
00:47:42.842 --> 00:47:46.782
who's going to talk to us about gene amplification, architecture, and expression.

818
00:47:52.522 --> 00:47:55.362
Okay. Hi, everyone. Thank you for being here.

819
00:47:55.742 --> 00:47:57.742
I want to say I have nothing to disclose.

820
00:47:58.722 --> 00:48:02.402
And I want to talk to you today about genome amplification

821
00:48:02.482 --> 00:48:06.282
architecture. So about one in five cancers

822
00:48:06.782 --> 00:48:10.182
amplify their oncogenes on extra chromosomal DNA or

823
00:48:10.222 --> 00:48:13.982
ecDNA, as opposed to within chromosomal

824
00:48:14.082 --> 00:48:17.462
regions called homogeneously staining regions or HSRs.

825
00:48:18.702 --> 00:48:22.282
And these two genome architectures produce very

826
00:48:22.322 --> 00:48:25.642
different patterns of copy number variation across cells in the

827
00:48:25.682 --> 00:48:29.202
population. So if you look across a tumor or a cell

828
00:48:29.222 --> 00:48:33.162
line, ecDNA-bearing cells show a broad, continuous

829
00:48:33.522 --> 00:48:36.682
distribution of copies per cell. In contrast,

830
00:48:36.922 --> 00:48:40.422
HSR-bearing cells produce this narrow, more uniform

831
00:48:40.522 --> 00:48:43.186
peak.And this difference is largely

832
00:48:44.046 --> 00:48:46.546
driven by how these elements are inherited.

833
00:48:46.866 --> 00:48:50.726
Chromosomes are inherited equally into daughter cells, while ecDNAs are

834
00:48:50.766 --> 00:48:53.076
unevenly segregated during cell division.

835
00:48:53.966 --> 00:48:57.426
And this uneven segregation of ecDNA produces a lot of

836
00:48:57.465 --> 00:49:01.006
diversity. So under drug pressure, this

837
00:49:01.066 --> 00:49:04.986
diversity may enable adaptation through a bet hedging

838
00:49:05.106 --> 00:49:08.866
strategy, where different cells with different levels of copies are

839
00:49:08.906 --> 00:49:10.616
primed for different environments.

840
00:49:12.036 --> 00:49:15.986
Another striking feature of ecDNA cancers are the structural

841
00:49:16.006 --> 00:49:19.846
plasticities. So these elements can be eliminated under

842
00:49:19.926 --> 00:49:23.496
drug pressure, and they can also reintegrate into chromosomes.

843
00:49:24.346 --> 00:49:27.916
And so today I want to focus on this plasticity, and I want to talk

844
00:49:28.006 --> 00:49:31.766
about where a gene is amplified or where it's located,

845
00:49:32.446 --> 00:49:36.426
whether it's on ecDNA or HSRs, will have different functional

846
00:49:36.526 --> 00:49:39.646
consequences at the gene, genome, and population level.

847
00:49:41.106 --> 00:49:43.986
So studying ecDNA is surprisingly challenging.

848
00:49:44.466 --> 00:49:47.866
In bulk whole-genome sequencing data, ecDNA is

849
00:49:47.946 --> 00:49:50.796
essentially indistinguishable from HSRs.

850
00:49:51.426 --> 00:49:55.136
So these two can have similar copy numbers, they can have

851
00:49:55.246 --> 00:49:58.886
similar gene expression levels, and they often amplify the

852
00:49:58.946 --> 00:50:02.306
same types of genes, which include oncogenes and regulatory

853
00:50:02.386 --> 00:50:06.286
elements. And so the only method that really distinguishes

854
00:50:06.326 --> 00:50:08.746
ecDNA and HSRs is

855
00:50:09.686 --> 00:50:12.266
fluorescence in situ hybridization or FISH.

856
00:50:12.826 --> 00:50:16.506
And in this approach, we use fluorescent probes that bind to specific

857
00:50:16.566 --> 00:50:20.426
DNA loci, and if those loci are amplified on

858
00:50:20.466 --> 00:50:23.966
ecDNA, you'll see these many dispersed

859
00:50:24.826 --> 00:50:28.366
puncta or signals that are shown here in this metaphase cell,

860
00:50:28.826 --> 00:50:32.606
where oncogenes like c-MYC, ERBB2, and CDC6 are all

861
00:50:32.666 --> 00:50:34.126
amplified on ecDNA.

862
00:50:35.066 --> 00:50:38.806
But the challenge with imaging is that it's low

863
00:50:39.146 --> 00:50:42.986
and very time intensive. If we want to quantify the number of

864
00:50:43.026 --> 00:50:46.406
ecDNA per cell or cell nuclei,

865
00:50:46.906 --> 00:50:50.785
this often requires manual counting, which does not

866
00:50:50.846 --> 00:50:54.706
scale. So to address this, my group has developed

867
00:50:54.966 --> 00:50:58.826
several AI-based methods to automate the detection and quantification of

868
00:50:58.866 --> 00:51:02.066
ecDNA from imaging data. We've also built

869
00:51:02.406 --> 00:51:06.266
resources to map ecDNA and HSRs

870
00:51:06.586 --> 00:51:09.006
across model systems. So for example,

871
00:51:09.466 --> 00:51:10.746
CytoCellDB,

872
00:51:11.786 --> 00:51:15.606
it's a resource that provides experimentally

873
00:51:15.706 --> 00:51:19.536
validated annotations for over 500 DepMap cell

874
00:51:19.586 --> 00:51:23.366
lines in order to help us better understand which systems harbor

875
00:51:23.426 --> 00:51:27.346
ecDNA versus HSRs. So with these tools in

876
00:51:27.446 --> 00:51:28.026
place,

877
00:51:28.946 --> 00:51:31.926
we can now turn to functional studies of ecDNA.

878
00:51:32.486 --> 00:51:36.186
And I want to start with one-- I want to introduce you to one model

879
00:51:36.286 --> 00:51:39.886
system that is found in this island here with

880
00:51:39.946 --> 00:51:43.346
high ERBB2 copy number variation and high ERBB2

881
00:51:43.386 --> 00:51:47.246
expression. And so taking this model system, we

882
00:51:47.286 --> 00:51:51.146
can better explore and understand the landscape of genes amplified on the

883
00:51:51.186 --> 00:51:54.876
ecDNA. We can also, with long-read sequencing, we can know the

884
00:51:54.986 --> 00:51:58.346
size of the ecDNA, which in this case is about three megabases.

885
00:52:00.126 --> 00:52:04.086
Importantly, when we do metaphase FISH experiments

886
00:52:04.146 --> 00:52:08.006
on this particular cell line, we can see that there's a broad

887
00:52:08.106 --> 00:52:11.526
range of ecDNA copies per cell from roughly

888
00:52:11.626 --> 00:52:15.146
100 to over 1,000. And this actually

889
00:52:15.186 --> 00:52:18.986
translates to a substantial difference in DNA burden

890
00:52:19.046 --> 00:52:22.906
with ecDNA comprising anywhere from about 4% in

891
00:52:22.966 --> 00:52:26.786
these low cells to about 30% of the total

892
00:52:26.826 --> 00:52:30.806
cellular DNA in these high cells. And what's interesting is

893
00:52:30.866 --> 00:52:34.746
that when we look at this in other ecDNA model systems, there seems to

894
00:52:34.786 --> 00:52:38.606
be a general phenomena here of this type of range.

895
00:52:39.906 --> 00:52:43.486
So we're interested in characterizing the difference between these

896
00:52:43.526 --> 00:52:45.946
extreme ends of this distribution.

897
00:52:46.546 --> 00:52:50.386
And in order to do that, we developed an

898
00:52:50.396 --> 00:52:51.306
approach to

899
00:52:52.246 --> 00:52:56.206
sort live cells. For this particular model

900
00:52:56.286 --> 00:52:59.906
system, we use an ecDNA proxy, which is HER2,

901
00:53:00.486 --> 00:53:02.775
an antibody which has a fluorophore attached.

902
00:53:03.246 --> 00:53:06.786
Because ERBB2 is amplified on ecDNA, HER2 is the

903
00:53:06.806 --> 00:53:10.196
encoding protein. So we reasoned that

904
00:53:10.206 --> 00:53:14.086
potentially high HER2 cells would have more ecDNA and low HER2

905
00:53:14.166 --> 00:53:18.126
cells would have less ecDNA. And we confirmed this through several different

906
00:53:18.146 --> 00:53:21.806
experiments. We performed FACS and collected these cells for

907
00:53:22.526 --> 00:53:25.306
metaphase FISH and indeed showed that high

908
00:53:26.186 --> 00:53:30.106
HER2 cells have much more ecDNA than low HER2

909
00:53:30.126 --> 00:53:33.846
cells. And they also have this graded relationship between

910
00:53:33.886 --> 00:53:37.396
HER2 intensity and ecDNA level. We also show that these

911
00:53:38.026 --> 00:53:41.466
have differences in total DNA with immunofluorescence assays.

912
00:53:42.166 --> 00:53:46.106
So this ability to isolate cells with these extreme ecDNA

913
00:53:46.146 --> 00:53:49.686
levels now allows us to perform functional genomic

914
00:53:49.766 --> 00:53:50.266
studies.

915
00:53:51.106 --> 00:53:51.486
So we

916
00:53:53.226 --> 00:53:56.926
collected Resolve-Om single-cell multi-omics data

917
00:53:57.026 --> 00:54:00.486
across six different cell lines, including those with

918
00:54:00.526 --> 00:54:04.326
ecDNA and HSRs. And this allows us to capture

919
00:54:04.366 --> 00:54:08.246
the entire genome, so whole genome and transcriptome from the

920
00:54:08.286 --> 00:54:12.206
same single cell. So we've produced this data on thousands of

921
00:54:12.246 --> 00:54:15.396
cells across these cell lines. And importantly, our data

922
00:54:15.506 --> 00:54:19.126
preserves this full distribution of ecDNA

923
00:54:19.146 --> 00:54:22.786
dosage across the cells that we see in our imaging experiments.

924
00:54:23.146 --> 00:54:23.966
We also see the

925
00:54:25.066 --> 00:54:28.566
clear relationship between HER2 protein and ecDNA

926
00:54:28.606 --> 00:54:29.986
dosage scaling.

927
00:54:30.866 --> 00:54:34.826
And then we asked a simple question, does the gene expression

928
00:54:34.906 --> 00:54:38.166
scale with ecDNA dosage, or do specific transcripts

929
00:54:38.246 --> 00:54:42.118
scale?And to answer this, we order the

930
00:54:42.158 --> 00:54:45.978
cells along this dosage trajectory by inferring ecDNA

931
00:54:46.018 --> 00:54:49.938
levels in every single cell. And then we quantify

932
00:54:50.018 --> 00:54:53.878
how different molecular layers, like DNA, RNA,

933
00:54:53.938 --> 00:54:56.478
and protein, co-vary with that dosage.

934
00:54:56.978 --> 00:55:00.438
So at the DNA level, you can see this very tight relationship

935
00:55:00.858 --> 00:55:04.398
between genes that are co-amplified on the same ecDNA.

936
00:55:05.228 --> 00:55:08.998
And this is to be expected. At the RNA level, we see more

937
00:55:09.038 --> 00:55:12.658
variability, but we also observe this coordinated scaling

938
00:55:13.118 --> 00:55:16.918
for both ecDNA amplified genes as well as some chromosomal

939
00:55:16.998 --> 00:55:20.418
non-amplified genes that are important to growth and translation.

940
00:55:21.058 --> 00:55:24.838
And at the protein level, HER2 abundance shows a very similar trend.

941
00:55:25.438 --> 00:55:28.478
And what we did next was really important.

942
00:55:28.618 --> 00:55:32.458
We wanted to compare these scaling relationships between ecDNA and

943
00:55:32.618 --> 00:55:36.058
HSR systems. And when we quantify the number of

944
00:55:36.118 --> 00:55:40.098
transcripts that significantly co-vary with dosage and

945
00:55:40.158 --> 00:55:44.048
how tightly they co-vary, how tightly they follow this relationship,

946
00:55:44.518 --> 00:55:48.258
we actually saw a very clear difference between ecDNA systems and

947
00:55:48.458 --> 00:55:52.258
HSR systems. And this suggests to us that coordinated

948
00:55:52.298 --> 00:55:55.498
gene expression scaling is an emergent

949
00:55:55.918 --> 00:55:58.718
population property of ecDNA biology.

950
00:55:59.878 --> 00:56:03.118
We then asked whether this architecture,

951
00:56:03.398 --> 00:56:07.098
ecDNA versus HSR, also changes how individual genes

952
00:56:07.138 --> 00:56:10.918
behave. So using the same data, we can look at

953
00:56:10.978 --> 00:56:14.858
transcriptional yield, or does more gene dosage equal

954
00:56:14.938 --> 00:56:18.878
more transcript? So we modeled transcriptional yield as a function of gene

955
00:56:18.918 --> 00:56:22.798
dosage. And what we found is that these are all genes that are

956
00:56:22.858 --> 00:56:26.578
amplified on the ecDNA, but they all have very different scaling behavior.

957
00:56:26.738 --> 00:56:30.538
Some have more linear scaling, while others have nonlinear and saturating

958
00:56:30.558 --> 00:56:34.358
dynamics. But what was really interesting to us

959
00:56:34.418 --> 00:56:38.378
is looking at how the scaling relationships change when ecDNA is

960
00:56:38.418 --> 00:56:40.118
reintegrated back into the chromosome.

961
00:56:41.018 --> 00:56:44.898
So we have a quasi-isogenic model system in which the parental

962
00:56:44.958 --> 00:56:48.518
line amplifies the same genes on

963
00:56:48.558 --> 00:56:52.098
ecDNA as a descendant line that amplifies them on

964
00:56:52.258 --> 00:56:55.858
HSRs. And when we compare the scaling relationships between

965
00:56:55.898 --> 00:56:59.758
these two model systems, we noticed that certain

966
00:56:59.858 --> 00:57:03.268
scaling relationships change very significantly, as shown by,

967
00:57:03.918 --> 00:57:05.298
for example, PVT1.

968
00:57:06.178 --> 00:57:09.718
So PVT1 is an oncogenic non-coding RNA.

969
00:57:10.318 --> 00:57:13.998
And when looking at our model system, we

970
00:57:14.078 --> 00:57:17.858
see the genes over in this area are the ones that scale the strongest with

971
00:57:17.898 --> 00:57:21.828
ecDNA dosage. So PVT1 happens to be one of the ones that

972
00:57:21.958 --> 00:57:25.918
scale the strongest. And what was very interesting

973
00:57:25.958 --> 00:57:27.018
to us is that

974
00:57:27.818 --> 00:57:31.798
the dominant isoform of PVT1, exon 1-2, shows

975
00:57:31.858 --> 00:57:35.258
this clear co-variation with ecDNA dosage,

976
00:57:35.758 --> 00:57:39.538
as well as with the Myc target gene expression program.

977
00:57:40.378 --> 00:57:44.098
And this is true for two or more

978
00:57:44.138 --> 00:57:47.598
ecDNA model systems that I'm showing here.

979
00:57:47.618 --> 00:57:51.298
But when you have the HSR state, this collapses and this

980
00:57:51.338 --> 00:57:54.998
coordination is lost. So this suggests that the genome

981
00:57:55.038 --> 00:57:58.398
architecture in this case directly tunes regulation and

982
00:57:58.418 --> 00:58:02.218
downstream transcriptional programming for Myc in this

983
00:58:02.258 --> 00:58:05.507
case. We next asked whether

984
00:58:05.538 --> 00:58:09.438
this heterogeneity is just a byproduct or

985
00:58:09.538 --> 00:58:13.218
whether it's something that might be actively maintained by these populations.

986
00:58:13.698 --> 00:58:17.618
And to test this, we sorted again our cells, our live cells, into high

987
00:58:17.658 --> 00:58:21.098
and low populations and cultured them separately.

988
00:58:21.738 --> 00:58:25.378
And then we tracked the number of ecDNAs per cell nucleus

989
00:58:25.578 --> 00:58:26.438
longitudinally

990
00:58:27.818 --> 00:58:31.258
over time. And what you can see here is a striking

991
00:58:31.658 --> 00:58:34.758
result that within two to three generations,

992
00:58:35.638 --> 00:58:39.228
both of these populations converge back to the original distribution.

993
00:58:40.198 --> 00:58:43.768
And this is a rapid restoration that suggests that maybe this

994
00:58:43.798 --> 00:58:47.638
heterogeneity is not just random, but actively regulated.

995
00:58:49.438 --> 00:58:52.498
And for this to happen, we think two things must be true.

996
00:58:53.278 --> 00:58:56.878
First, the inheritance, as shown by this model, has to be

997
00:58:56.998 --> 00:59:00.637
biased, with ecDNA unevenly distributing more

998
00:59:00.697 --> 00:59:04.018
often than not or more often than expected by chance.

999
00:59:04.618 --> 00:59:08.358
And then the cells with higher levels of ecDNA may have a growth

1000
00:59:08.418 --> 00:59:11.898
advantage, so they proceed through the cell cycle faster.

